-- Singapore index advances to near 4-month high
-- By Brian Leonal
-- Mon Mar 31, 2014 12:21AM EDT
-- None



SINGAPORE, March 31 (Reuters) - Singapore's main index rose for a fourth straight session on Monday to its highest in nearly four months, in line with the broader Asian market that rode on expectations of potential stimulus in China.

The Straits Times index <.FTSTI> advanced as much as 20.16 points, or 0.64 percent, to 3,192.3, its highest since Dec. 3, 2013. MSCI's broadest index of Asia-Pacific shares outside Japan <.MIAPJ0000PUS> rose more than 0.3 percent on heightened speculation that Beijing will launch new spending measures and on easing tensions in Ukraine. [ID:nL4N0MP27V] Among gainers, Thai Beverage PCL <TBEV.SI> topped the Singapore index and rose as much as 3.4 percent to an intra-day high of S$0.61, on track for its biggest daily gain in nearly four weeks. Real estate stocks figured among the top performers. CapitaMalls Asia Ltd <CMAL.SI> and CapitaLand Ltd <CATL.SI> rose 2.5 percent and 2.1 percent, respectively. The real estate index <.FTFSTAS8600> gained 0.3 percent to an 11-week high.